ibe?url=http%3A%2F%2Ffeeds.feedburner.com%2FNumberNeededToTreat" src="http://www.wikio.com/shared/img/add2wikio.gif">Subscribe with Wikio</feedburner:feedFlare><feedburner:feedFlare href="http://www.dailyrotation.com/index.php?feed=http%3A%2F%2Ffeeds.feedburner.com%2FNumberNeededToTreat" src="http://www.dailyrotation.com/rss-dr2.gif">Subscribe with Daily Rotation</feedburner:feedFlare><item><title>Netter's Atlas on the iPad</title><description>&lt;a href="http://www.tuaw.com/2011/09/26/daily-ipad-app-netters-anatomy-atlas/"&gt;Netter's Atlas on the iPad&lt;/a&gt;: &lt;p&gt;Non-med site story about the iconic anatomy atlas on the iPad.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;By the way, that color-coded skull on the app icon haunts me. There aren’t many bones that fit together to make the skull, but their relationships to one another are complex. I don’t know how neurosurgeons and ENTs do it. And it may look like it’s smiling, but make no mistake…that’s an evil grin.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~4/adGLPf6kmrY" height="1" width="1"/&gt;</description><link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~3/adGLPf6kmrY/10712140750</link><guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/10712140750</guid><pubDate>Mon, 26 Sep 2011 20:55:00 -0500</pubDate><category>Netter's Human Anatomy Atlas</category><category>iPad</category><category>anatomy</category><feedburner:origLink>http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/10712140750</feedburner:origLink></item><item><title>Why I left a top children's hospital for a private office</title><description>&lt;a href="http://www.kevinmd.com/blog/2011/09/left-top-childrens-hospital-private-office.html"&gt;Why I left a top children's hospital for a private office&lt;/a&gt;: &lt;p&gt;This is an excellent piece giving a personal touch to the dichotomy between academic medicine and private practice.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I see myself struggling with this decision in the future. Given my background and research experience, I picture myself practicing in academic medicine. However, private practice offers so many things, most of all the opportunity to practice medicine on your own terms. Bureaucracy runs rampant in academic medical institutions—something I’m all too familiar with—which can hinder clinicians who take a creative approach to patient care. The added pressures of bringing in research dollars and providing education I’m sure are oppressive at times. At the same time, working on cutting edge research and sharing your knowledge and wisdom with the next generation of physicians is likely very rewarding.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;At this point in my career, I try to continually remind myself to focus on what is immediately in front of me and hope such large decisions figure themselves out for the best.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~4/fthiWA2976Q" height="1" width="1"/&gt;</description><link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~3/fthiWA2976Q/10684612802</link><guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/10684612802</guid><pubDate>Mon, 26 Sep 2011 07:00:05 -0500</pubDate><category>academic medicine</category><category>private practice</category><feedburner:origLink>http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/10684612802</feedburner:origLink></item><item><title>"Surely there is something absurd when a nation pays a primary care physician poorly relative to..."</title><description>“Surely there is something absurd when a nation pays a primary care physician poorly relative to other specialists and then wrings its hands over a shortage of primary care physicians.”&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt; - &lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Uwe Reinhardt&lt;/strong&gt;, Princeton University economist&lt;/em&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~4/VsPvFzPw8ik" height="1" width="1"/&gt;</description><link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~3/VsPvFzPw8ik/10523996610</link><guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/10523996610</guid><pubDate>Thu, 22 Sep 2011 13:03:05 -0500</pubDate><category>medicine</category><category>health economics</category><category>Health Policy</category><feedburner:origLink>http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/10523996610</feedburner:origLink></item><item><title>ourownsystem:

MobiHealthNews thinks the number of consumer...</title><description>&lt;img src="http://25.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lrxgpxHeQs1qzv4oao1_500.jpg"/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://ourownsystem.com/post/10518585765" target="_blank"&gt;ourownsystem&lt;/a&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://mobihealthnews.com/13368/report-13k-iphone-consumer-health-apps-in-2012/" target="_blank"&gt;MobiHealthNews thinks&lt;/a&gt; the number of consumer iPhone health apps will number 13,000 in 2012. That’s a lot. But we still await a platform to tie everything together.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~4/M7NoqoNFdRQ" height="1" width="1"/&gt;</description><link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~3/M7NoqoNFdRQ/10519014246</link><guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/10519014246</guid><pubDate>Thu, 22 Sep 2011 09:34:04 -0500</pubDate><feedburner:origLink>http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/10519014246</feedburner:origLink></item><item><title>How one small group sets doctors' pay</title><description>&lt;a href="http://well.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/09/22/how-one-small-group-sets-doctors-pay/"&gt;How one small group sets doctors' pay&lt;/a&gt;: &lt;p&gt;This is an excellent primer on how exactly physician pay is determined in this country. If you are a physician or medical student and do not know what the RUC is, you need to read this article.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Only five of the 29 physicians that compose the RUC are from primary care fields. We can give med students who go into primary care free med school and lavish upon them conferences, seminars, and mentorship programs to pique (and hold) their interest in primary care. But little will change unless the composition of the RUC is adjusted to reflect the true value primary care provides within our health care system.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~4/EzL50zWDOuw" height="1" width="1"/&gt;</description><link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~3/EzL50zWDOuw/10518833631</link><guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/10518833631</guid><pubDate>Thu, 22 Sep 2011 09:24:16 -0500</pubDate><category>medicine</category><category>health economics</category><category>Health Policy</category><category>health care reform</category><category>med students</category><category>med school debt</category><feedburner:origLink>http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/10518833631</feedburner:origLink></item><item><title>FaceTime calls are encrypted, HIPAA compliant</title><description>&lt;a href="http://www.tuaw.com/2011/09/21/facetime-calls-are-encrypted-hipaa-compliant/"&gt;FaceTime calls are encrypted, HIPAA compliant&lt;/a&gt;: &lt;p&gt;Let the telemedicine begin! No longer will doctors and patients need expensive, confusing setups to conduct distance visits. To be fair, I guess some people think iPads are expensive and confusing…&lt;/p&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~4/gutTEKq9nsA" height="1" width="1"/&gt;</description><link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~3/gutTEKq9nsA/10483046938</link><guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/10483046938</guid><pubDate>Wed, 21 Sep 2011 11:16:31 -0500</pubDate><category>iPad</category><category>apple</category><category>telemedicine</category><feedburner:origLink>http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/10483046938</feedburner:origLink></item><item><title>Practice Fusion raises an additional $6 million</title><description>&lt;a href="http://tcrn.ch/rs3PMt"&gt;Practice Fusion raises an additional $6 million&lt;/a&gt;: &lt;p&gt;Practice Fusion—a web-based electronic medical record system available for free to physicians—has just raised $6 million from various investors. This brings their total funding up to $36 million.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~4/8rpwaPzdwYs" height="1" width="1"/&gt;</description><link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~3/8rpwaPzdwYs/10441983263</link><guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/10441983263</guid><pubDate>Tue, 20 Sep 2011 09:13:17 -0500</pubDate><category>medicine</category><category>electronic medical records</category><category>EMR</category><feedburner:origLink>http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/10441983263</feedburner:origLink></item><item><title>In a nod to John Halamka’s “Cool Technology of the...</title><description>&lt;img src="http://25.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lrswuxKJM71qb6lheo1_500.jpg"/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;p&gt;In a nod to &lt;a href="http://geekdoctor.blogspot.com/2011/09/cool-technology-of-week_16.html" target="_blank"&gt;John Halamka’s “Cool Technology of the Week”&lt;/a&gt; series, I present to you the &lt;a href="https://vitaband.net/home" target="_blank"&gt;VITAband&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Essentially, VITAband is a silicone wristband you wear when going on those long runs or lengthy bike rides that serves as both a medical ID bracelet and credit card. In case of an emergency where you can’t provide relevant information, first responders call the VITAband hotline, give them the ID number printed on the bracelet and then are given your medical info (blood type, allergies, health insurance, emergency contacts, etc). The band also contains a &lt;a target="_blank" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Near_field_communication"&gt;near field communication&lt;/a&gt; chip that serves as a credit card so you can pickup a Gatorade at the gas station without having to pull sweaty cash from your sock.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A medical ID bracelet that doubles as a credit card - that’s cool!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;[via &lt;a href="http://gearpatrol.com/blog/2011/09/15/vitaband/" target="_blank"&gt;Gear Patrol&lt;/a&gt;]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~4/7ezFkir0sos" height="1" width="1"/&gt;</description><link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~3/7ezFkir0sos/10430846914</link><guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/10430846914</guid><pubDate>Mon, 19 Sep 2011 22:11:00 -0500</pubDate><category>cool technology</category><feedburner:origLink>http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/10430846914</feedburner:origLink></item><item><title>Blog update - shift in content focus</title><description>&lt;p&gt;Although I’ve never strictly limited the topics I talk about here, I’ve tried to keep it relatively focused. I originally started this blog before I began medical school and largely used it as a platform to discuss the misrepresentation of medical research and health policy in mainstream media. I was just out of grad school and heavily focused on epidemiological principles and health services research. After starting med school two years ago, I started bringing in my experiences from the preclinical years and focusing a lot on medical education.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I am once again shifting focuses in my professional life and as such intend to shift the focus of this blog a little. In the past few months, I finished up my second year of med school, took the first round of boards (USMLE Step 1) and started a new job. (This is the reason behind so few posts in recent months.) I am now taking a year off from med school to do some research and work on mobile app development.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Given my new position, I will (hopefully) be writing more and more about technology and medicine, specifically mobile technology. I’ve written about these topics before, but they will be at the forefront until I start my third year of med school in June 2012.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As always, feel free to email me any questions [josh AT joshherigon DOT com]. Hope you enjoy some of the new content!&lt;/p&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~4/YK_qo_kzrPE" height="1" width="1"/&gt;</description><link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~3/YK_qo_kzrPE/10226047395</link><guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/10226047395</guid><pubDate>Wed, 14 Sep 2011 21:04:49 -0500</pubDate><feedburner:origLink>http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/10226047395</feedburner:origLink></item><item><title>"Do you concur Dr. Watson?"</title><description>&lt;a href="http://news.cnet.com/8301-11386_3-20104614-76/ibms-watson-to-offer-medical-advice-to-doctors/"&gt;"Do you concur Dr. Watson?"&lt;/a&gt;: &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://ourownsystem.com/post/10122494893" target="_blank"&gt;ourownsystem&lt;/a&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;CNET:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;IBM has inked a deal with health insurer WellPoint that will let WellPoint use the technology behind “Jeopardy”-playing computer Watson to suggest patient diagnoses and treatments.&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I find it telling about the state of our health care system—and who exactly is in charge—that this promising new technology is going to be used by an insurance company and not academic researchers working in quality improvement.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~4/GVBSggqIkFw" height="1" width="1"/&gt;</description><link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~3/GVBSggqIkFw/10125878959</link><guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/10125878959</guid><pubDate>Mon, 12 Sep 2011 09:39:44 -0500</pubDate><category>technology</category><category>quality improvement</category><category>health economics</category><category>health insurance</category><feedburner:origLink>http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/10125878959</feedburner:origLink></item><item><title>Citing Wikipedia in a formal research paper</title><description>&lt;p&gt;I tweeted the following earlier:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;How kosher is it to cite Wikipedia in a formal, peer-reviewed medical paper? #meded&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The replies that came back basically said to cite the underlying citation in the Wikipedia article for the piece of information I wanted to cite. Great suggestion and prudent in most situations. However, for my particular situation, the underlying sources cited in the Wikipedia article aren’t peer-reviewed journal articles so I don’t think they add any value.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Basically, I’m looking for a source to define what exactly a “smartphone” is for the background section of an empiric research paper I’m writing. One option would be to cite a dictionary definition. I looked at a few such definitions. Some are decent, but they lack a richness in their definitions. The &lt;a target="_blank" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smartphone"&gt;Wikipedia article on smartphones&lt;/a&gt; provides much more detail on what is a rather nebulous and dynamic term. Another option is to look for peer-reviewed journal articles that use the term and see how they have defined the term and their citations. Unfortunately, this is such a new area of research that I’m not finding very many articles on the subject.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This highlights a problem with our current peer-reviewed systems of research publication—journals have a hard time keeping pace with quickly evolving areas such as technology.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The question remains—when is it acceptable to cite a source like Wikipedia in formal, peer-reviewed research papers?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~4/epjpWl9aQes" height="1" width="1"/&gt;</description><link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~3/epjpWl9aQes/9868241222</link><guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/9868241222</guid><pubDate>Mon, 05 Sep 2011 23:54:31 -0500</pubDate><category>med research</category><category>Med School</category><category>meded</category><category>research</category><feedburner:origLink>http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/9868241222</feedburner:origLink></item><item><title>"Baby boomers have been misled — by themselves or by technology vendors, it isn’t clear — to believe..."</title><description>“Baby boomers have been misled — by themselves or by technology vendors, it isn’t clear — to believe that there is some magic by which “the computer” imparts knowledge faster or more efficiently than traditional modes of education…The basic facts of education haven’t changed since the dawn of the personal computer: reading, writing, and arithmetic are still at the core. In ink or in liquid crystal, the alphabet is just as easy or as difficult to master as it always was and will continue to be.”&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt; - &lt;em&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Jared Sinclair&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a target="_blank" href="http://jaredsinclair.com/post/9785602420/technology-in-the-classroom-fails-to-improve-scores"&gt;commenting&lt;/a&gt; on a &lt;a target="_blank" href="http://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/04/technology/technology-in-schools-faces-questions-on-value.html?_r=1&amp;hp&amp;pagewanted=all"&gt;NY Times piece discussing technology’s impact on education&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I would amend this sentiment to include almost all of us, not just baby boomers, among those who have put blind faith in the “magic” of technology to improve learning. I’m am certainly guilty of this myself in my very own education. I’ve thought in the past that if I could just find the right app or website to teach me a concept, I would be able to master something in half the time it would take to learn about it in a book.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Another way to sum up this sentiment—technology in education provides convenience; it doesn’t make the educational process shorter or easier. Moreover, when done poorly, technology can serve as a barrier as people spend energy mastering the technology instead of the material they are studying.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Thus, two questions should be considered when incorporating technology into an educational activity:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;&lt;li&gt;Does the technology provide greater convenience to the learner (at a minimal cost in terms of money, time, educational efficiency, etc)?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Is the technology sufficiently common or easily understood so as to not create an additional challenge to learning the material?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;&lt;p&gt;These questions need to be considered carefully in medical schools throughout the United States. Medical schools have always been early adopters of technology in their curricula (due to this faith in technology to improve learning efficiency), however, few seem to carefully consider its true cost-benefit ratio (outside of what it will cost the school monetarily and whether or not they can pass that cost on to the student—in which case they don’t care at all about cost).&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~4/BkIdoVoYPCM" height="1" width="1"/&gt;</description><link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~3/BkIdoVoYPCM/9794481327</link><guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/9794481327</guid><pubDate>Sun, 04 Sep 2011 12:08:56 -0500</pubDate><category>med education</category><category>Med School</category><category>med students</category><feedburner:origLink>http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/9794481327</feedburner:origLink></item><item><title>"Do you want to sell sugar water for the rest of your life or come with me and change the world?"</title><description>“Do you want to sell sugar water for the rest of your life or come with me and change the world?”&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt; - &lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Steve Jobs&lt;/strong&gt;—according to &lt;a target="_blank" href="http://www.tuaw.com/2011/08/25/a-list-of-steve-jobss-best-quotes/"&gt;TUAW&lt;/a&gt;, this is the line Jobs used to lure John Sculley away from Pepsi.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~4/rnmXcpVkL1M" height="1" width="1"/&gt;</description><link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~3/rnmXcpVkL1M/9380908602</link><guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/9380908602</guid><pubDate>Thu, 25 Aug 2011 13:05:19 -0500</pubDate><category>non-med related</category><category>steve jobs</category><category>technology</category><feedburner:origLink>http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/9380908602</feedburner:origLink></item><item><title>"It’s hard to imagine that we’ll ever see another 15 years of blockbuster, culture-changing hits like..."</title><description>“It’s hard to imagine that we’ll ever see another 15 years of blockbuster, culture-changing hits like the iMac, iPod, iPhone and iPad — from Apple or anyone else. And that’s really, really sad. Thank you, Mr. Jobs, for an incredible run. The worlds of culture, media and technology have never seen anything like you. In your new role, we wish you health, rest and happiness — and, whenever you feel up to it, the opportunity to let Apple know where the puck will come to rest.”&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt; - &lt;em&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;David Pogue&lt;/strong&gt; writing on his &lt;a target="_blank" href="http://pogue.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/08/25/steve-jobs-reshaped-industries/"&gt;NY Times blog&lt;/a&gt; about the resignation of Steve Jobs&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Well written (as usual) from Pogue. I only want to add emphasis to his last line—all the best health-wise to Steve Jobs.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~4/444IM0dmnPE" height="1" width="1"/&gt;</description><link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~3/444IM0dmnPE/9373504922</link><guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/9373504922</guid><pubDate>Thu, 25 Aug 2011 08:11:26 -0500</pubDate><category>non-med related</category><category>Steve Jobs</category><category>Apple</category><feedburner:origLink>http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/9373504922</feedburner:origLink></item><item><title>Junk food: Less soda, thinner kids</title><description>&lt;a href="http://www.boston.com/lifestyle/health/articles/2011/08/23/junk_food_less_soda_thinner_kids/"&gt;Junk food: Less soda, thinner kids&lt;/a&gt;: &lt;p&gt;Some evidence showing ban on sugary drinks makes a difference in daily caloric intake of children.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;One thing not talked about when discussing such bans is the message this sends to children when we put such measures in place. Hopefully, the message is that consumption of these drinks is not for every day. When soft drinks were originally introduced, they were something of a treat. People would go to the soda fountain for a special occasion or as a weekend ritual and consume (I’m guessing here) drinks that were in the 12 oz range. Today, we have people—many of them children—consuming 20+ ozs on a daily basis. If we could get back to a more rational consumption of sugary drinks, we wouldn’t need to be discussing bans or extra taxes on sugary drinks.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~4/VCxlGG8Bc_g" height="1" width="1"/&gt;</description><link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/NumberNeededToTreat/~3/VCxlGG8Bc_g/9291735159</link><guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/9291735159</guid><pubDate>Tue, 23 Aug 2011 08:32:23 -0500</pubDate><category>Pediatrics</category><category>sugary drinks</category><category>obesity</category><feedburner:origLink>http://blog.joshherigon.com/post/9291735159</feedburner:origLink></item></channel></rss>
